<author><name><![CDATA[psycopathicteen]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-09-28T15:50:46-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-09-28T15:50:46-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11670&amp;p=134386#p134386</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11670&amp;p=134386#p134386"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Ideal size for homebrew.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11670&amp;p=134386#p134386"><![CDATA[
I'm guessing a good goal would be to fill up 4 megabits, or 512 kB.  With that size you would have enough room to make a good game, but you wouldn't be tempted in going overboard on features.  ROM could be divided up like this:<br /><br />128kB for level maps (8 levels, each 16kB large)<br />64kB for audio<br />32kB for program code<br />128kB for BG graphics (8 sets of 16kB)<br />160kB for sprite graphics<br /><br />You can probably cut down on sprite graphics by using a lot of software rotation and scaling tricks.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4383">psycopathicteen</a> — Sun Sep 28, 2014 3:50 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
